{"key":"post-13167724","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>13167724</id>\n<content>Most substrate materials already have a slightly acidic pH, which is what mushroom mycelium prefers.&amp;nbsp; In addition to supplying calcium and sulfur, and helping to prevent substrate clumping, a side-benefit of gypsum is it tends to keep the pH stable, preventing wild swings in either direction.&amp;nbsp; If you use gypsum in your bulk substrate, you can pretty much ignore pH if you're using common materials such as manure or coir, straw, etc.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>13167732</next>\n<prev>13167680</prev>\n<first>13164584</first>\n<last>13169087</last>\n<when>1284000730</when>\n<utime>09/09/10 05:52 AM</utime>\n</post>"}